{"id":14881291,"mediaExerciseId":"2d51f7dd-6b18-428d-a8b1-c28fc026f0a9","exerciseName":"6","chapterName":"11","chapterTitle":"Project Analysis and Evaluation","groupId":612351,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":375,"solutions":[{"id":6059239,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"Before we get to answer this, we must first quickly review the difference between these break-even points. \n\n**Accounting break-even point** refers to the amount of sales where the profit will equal zero. \n\n**Cash break-even point** refers to the amount of sales where the cashflow is zero. This means that the net profit is negative. \n\n**Financial break-even point** refers to the point where the net present value (NPV) is equal to zero. This means that the current value of your cashflow is less than the initial investment. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"As a shareholder, you should be more concerned about the **financial break-even point** since it is a good measure of your return of investment (ROI). Since the company is contemplating a new project, it is useful to first identify how long it would take for you to start profiting from the investment. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"22a35791-e650-4d36-a785-7cddde96391c","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":2}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of